{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17522483","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17522483"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:45:52+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:45:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13833"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13833","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13833"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.06,0.56,0.25,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6450"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50002"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6450"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13833"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35255"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1197"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2873"},{"type":"tags","id":"7982"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"12752"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12753"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13934"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50002","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50002"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 43-year-old man presents to his General Practice clinic with a three-month history of persistent cough, fatigue, and generalised muscle aches. He reports occasional blood-tinged sputum and nasal congestion. Over the same time period he has developed some painless scabs on his feet (Image 1, 2). He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears unwell with a pulse rate of 90/min, blood pressure 130/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. Chest auscultation reveals scattered crackles bilaterally. Laboratory investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 110 g/L (130-170)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMean corpuscular volume: 85 fL (80-100)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 12 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelet count: 450 x 10^9/L (150-400)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine: 120 \u03bcmol/L (60-110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERheumatoid factor: Positive\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrinalysis: 2+ blood, 1+ protein\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Rheumatoid arthritis","Systemic lupus erythematosus","Granulomatosis with polyangiitis","Goodpasture syndrome","Sarcoidosis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most likely diagnosis is \u003Cstrong\u003Egranulomatosis with polyangiitis (GPA)\u003C/strong\u003E, previously known as Wegener\u0027s granulomatosis. This condition is characterised by necrotising granulomatous inflammation and vasculitis in small- and medium-sized blood vessels, primarily affecting the upper and lower respiratory tracts and kidneys.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe patient\u0027s presentation with persistent cough, blood-tinged sputum, nasal congestion, ulcers and palpable purpura on the feet, and constitutional symptoms (fatigue, muscle aches) is typical for GPA. The laboratory findings of normocytic anaemia, leukocytosis, thrombocytosis, elevated creatinine, and urinary abnormalities (haematuria and proteinuria) further support this diagnosis. There may also be an elevated erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR) and c-Antineutrophil cytoplasmic antibody (c-ANCA) is positive in 70% of patients. While rheumatoid factor positivity is more commonly associated with rheumatoid arthritis, it can also be positive in up to 50% of cases of GPA and may indicate poor prognostic factors for ANCA-associated vasculitis. Treatment typically involves immunosuppression with corticosteroids and other agents such as cyclophosphamide or rituximab.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERheumatoid arthritis\u003C/strong\u003E primarily affects the joints and typically presents with symmetrical joint pain and swelling, which are not prominent features in this case. While rheumatoid arthritis can have extra-articular manifestations, the combination of respiratory and renal involvement is more suggestive of GPA.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESarcoidosis\u003C/strong\u003E can present with respiratory symptoms and fatigue, but it typically does not cause significant renal involvement or haematuria. Additionally, sarcoidosis is not associated with positive rheumatoid factor or anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystemic lupus erythematosus (SLE)\u003C/strong\u003E can affect multiple organ systems, including the lungs and kidneys. However, the absence of characteristic features such as malar rash, photosensitivity, or arthritis makes SLE less likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGoodpasture syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (anti-glomerular basement membrane disease) is characterised by glomerulonephritis and pulmonary hemorrhage, which can present with cough, haemoptysis and anaemia. However, it typically affects younger individuals, is not associated with ulcers or palpable purpura, and does not usually cause upper respiratory tract symptoms or granulomatous inflammation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Granulomatosis with polyangiitis (GPA) is characterised by necrotising granulomatous inflammation and vasculitis in small- and medium-sized blood vessels.","Common presenting features of GPA include upper and lower respiratory tract symptoms, renal involvement, and constitutional symptoms.","ANCA (particularly c-ANCA) is positive in most cases of GPA, but rheumatoid factor can also be positive in some patients."],"references":["Sinovich V, Oakley A. Granulomatosis with polyangiitis. In Dermnetnz. 2016. [online]. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/granulomatosis-with-polyangiitis","Watanabe S, Gono T, Nishina K, Sugitani N, Watanabe E, Yabe H, Terai C. Rhematoid factor is correlated with disease activity and inflammatory markers in antineutrophil cytoplasmic antibody-associated vasculitis. BMC Immunology. 2017 (53). Available at: https://bmcimmunol.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s12865-017-0234-8"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35255"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13833"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20780"},{"type":"media","id":"20781"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20780","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20780"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fo8TpD7xljUprXkn1VdqgRoa9eRTMK.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fo8TpD7xljUprXkn1VdqgRoa9eRTMK.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1024,"height":768}},{"type":"media","id":"20781","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20781"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Mgofmayi6Z6WOGW6JpKDcRd4r089vX.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/Mgofmayi6Z6WOGW6JpKDcRd4r089vX.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1024,"height":768}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35255","links":{"self":"https:/